[b][u]HomeKitLink Siri (HKLS)[/u][/b]

HomeKitLink Siri is an Indigo plugin that creates native HomeKit Bridges — exposing your Indigo devices to Apple HomeKit and Siri control. No Homebridge. No external server. Everything runs inside Indigo.

[b]Current Version:[/b] 0.8.05   |   [b]Requires:[/b] Indigo 2022.1+ (Python 3)
[b]GitHub:[/b] [url=https://github.com/Ghawken/HomeKitLink-Siri]https://github.com/Ghawken/HomeKitLink-Siri[/url]
[b]Full Documentation / Wiki:[/b] [url=https://github.com/Ghawken/HomeKitLink-Siri/wiki]https://github.com/Ghawken/HomeKitLink-Siri/wiki[/url]

[img]https://github.com/Ghawken/HomeKitLink-Siri/blob/main/Images/divider.gif?raw=true[/img]

[size=150][u]What It Does[/u][/size]

Create one or more [b]HomeKitLink Bridge[/b] devices inside Indigo. Each bridge acts as a HomeKit accessory bridge — pair it once with a QR code in the iOS Home app, and every Indigo device you publish to it appears automatically in HomeKit and is controllable via Siri.

[b]Key Features:[/b]
- Unlimited bridges (up to 95 Indigo devices each)
- Lights — colour, colour temperature, dimmer, switch — auto-detected subtype
- Fans — simple and speed-controlled (Fan V2)
- Switches, Outlets, Action Groups
- All sensor types — temperature, humidity, motion, occupancy, contact, luminance, smoke, CO, leak
- Blinds and Windows — with position and inversion options
- Thermostats, Locks, Garage Doors, Valves
- Security Systems — Paradox, DSC, VSS, AD2USB
- Cameras — Blue Iris and SecuritySpy with live video, Opus audio, motion detection, doorbell
- Full Siri control once paired
- All configuration stored in the Indigo database — migrates with Indigo

[img]https://github.com/Ghawken/HomeKitLink-Siri/blob/main/Images/divider.gif?raw=true[/img]

[size=150][u]Quick Start[/u][/size]

[b]1.[/b] Install from the Plugin Store or download from [url=https://github.com/Ghawken/HomeKitLink-Siri/releases]GitHub Releases[/url]
[b]2.[/b] In Indigo: Devices → New Device → Plugin → HomeKitLink Siri → HomeKitLink Bridge
[b]3.[/b] Select a device, check Publish, choose HomeKit type, click Save Device. Repeat for more devices.
[b]4.[/b] Click Save in the dialog to start the bridge.
[b]5.[/b] Open the bridge config → Show QR Code
[b]6.[/b] iOS Home app → + → Add Accessory → scan QR code
[b]7.[/b] Done. Siri can now control your devices.

[img]https://github.com/Ghawken/HomeKitLink-Siri/blob/main/Images/DeviceConfig1.png?raw=true[/img]

[b]Limits:[/b] Each Indigo device can be published to one bridge only. 95 devices max per bridge — create more bridges as needed (unlimited).

[img]https://github.com/Ghawken/HomeKitLink-Siri/blob/main/Images/divider.gif?raw=true[/img]

[size=150][u]Plugin Menu Items[/u][/size]

[img]https://github.com/Ghawken/HomeKitLink-Siri/blob/main/Images/MenuItems_new.png?raw=true[/img]

[size=125][b][u]⚠️ Before Posting — Run These Three Items First ⚠️[/u][/b][/size]

[b]These diagnostic tools solve the vast majority of issues. Please run all three and include the Indigo log output in any forum post. Without this output, diagnosing your issue is much harder.[/b]

[b]Plugins → HomeKitLink Siri →[/b]

[b]ℹ️ Troubleshoot 1 — Support Information For Forum Posting[/b]
Generates a complete summary of your HKLS installation: plugin version, Python version, all configured bridges, published device list, mDNS/network configuration, active drivers, port assignments, and any known error conditions. [b]Include this in every support post.[/b]

[b]ℹ️ Troubleshoot 2 — Network Trouble Shooting[/b]
Comprehensive network diagnostic. Checks: Apple Local Network Access (macOS Sequoia 15.x+ requirement), mDNS multicast send and group join, outbound UDP, gateway reachability, firewall status (stealth mode, block-all), plugin network config, bridge port accessibility, and DNS resolution. Uses a definitive multicast send test that catches the exact LNA failure mode.

[b]ℹ️ Troubleshoot 3 — Support mDNS Troubleshooting[/b]
Focused mDNS/Bonjour diagnostic. Checks: interface binding, firewall as it relates to mDNS, Zeroconf/AsyncZeroconf state, Bonjour/mDNSResponder status, and mDNS advertisement records for all active bridges.

[b]macOS Sequoia (15.x+) users:[/b] Run Troubleshoot 2 first — it will tell you definitively if Local Network Access is blocked. If it is: System Settings → Privacy & Security → Local Network → enable IndigoPluginHost3.

[b]Other menu items:[/b]
- [b]Show Device Publications[/b] — lists all published devices in the Indigo log with status (running / disabled / orphaned)
- [b]Identify Devices Running / Not Running[/b] — shows which bridges are active
- [b]Restart HomeKit[/b] — stops and restarts all bridges
- [b]Unlink Orphaned Devices[/b] — cleans up devices whose bridge was deleted
- [b]Delete Residual States Files[/b] — removes leftover HomeKit state files
- [b]Rerun FFmpeg Call for Logging[/b] — replays last camera stream command, logs full FFmpeg output
- [b]Check or Update Camera Streams for Compatibility[/b] — runs ffprobe against all cameras, logs compatibility analysis (run after changing Blue Iris stream settings)
- [b]Debug Log Menu Options[/b] — internal debug: bridges, drivers, threads, accessories, device list
- [b]Move Accessories to Another Bridge[/b] — recovery tool if a bridge was accidentally deleted
- [b]Reset Accessory / Bridge[/b] — deletes security keys for a bridge (use before re-pairing a broken bridge)

